# Gamma 4 Harness

This repository contains the Offline Local Coding Harness built specifically for local inference (running Gemma 4 E4B models via Ollama on constrained hardware). It allows for powerful offline agentic coding with a clear trace stream and built-in file writing approvals.

## High-Level Architecture
The project is built as a TypeScript monorepo containing front-end applications, a backend API, CLI interfaces, and several isolated Node.js packages representing the core engine logic. 

## Directory and File Breakdown

### Root Configuration and Documentation
- `AGENTS.md` and `AGENTS_local_harness.md`: These files define the build contract, objectives, and parameters for creating this specific agent harness. It functions as a source of truth for the repository structure and operational limits.
- `README.md`: The general repository README containing quick-start instructions.
- `gamma4.readme`: This file, explaining the internal file structure of the workspace in details.
- `docker-compose.yml`, `Dockerfile.api`, `Dockerfile.web`: Container definitions that allow deploying the web interface and API service reliably across systems.
- `nginx.conf`: Proxies requests locally for Docker setups to ensure Web and API servers can communicate seamlessly.
- `package.json` and `package-lock.json`: The monorepo NPM workspace configuration handling all dependencies and builds across `apps/` and `packages/` workspaces.
- `.dockerignore`, `.gamma-harness`: Docker exclusions and local harness state kept outside normal project source.

### Applications (`apps/`)
This folder contains the primary runnable entry points of the system.
- `apps/cli/`: 
  The terminal interface. It supports command-style usage (`doctor`, `benchmark`, `prompt`, `session`, `workspace`, `skills`, `model`, `config`) and also offers interactive REPL chat with slash commands.
- `apps/api/`:
  The backend API service that interacts with the Web application, resolving frontend requests over HTTP to the `core` engine.
- `apps/web/`:
  The Localhost Web UI which provides a Graphical User Interface to track trace events, view active tools, approve file modifications, and switch skills seamlessly.

### Core Engine and Libraries (`packages/`)
This isolates specific functional responsibilities into testable TypeScript modules.
- `@local-harness/approval-workflow`: Intercepts filesystem-modifying tools, prompting the user (via CLI or UI queue) before making potentially dangerous writes.
- `@local-harness/core`: The main brain. Binds all packages together, tracking session flows and dispatching tool/agent actions.
- `@local-harness/doctor`: System diagnostics checker ensuring Ollama health and proper system dependencies (`harness doctor`).
- `@local-harness/model-adapter`: Safely manages communication sequences with Ollama and OpenAI-flavored /v1 endpoints, handling streaming generation logs.
- `@local-harness/planner`: Orchestrates the action-plan chain, keeping the model anchored to the main objective without rambling.
- `@local-harness/prompt-recipes`: Pre-built system contexts and tool templates extracted from advanced references.
- `@local-harness/repo-indexer`: A retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) feature that allows the model to search through the current project workspace.
- `@local-harness/session-store`: Saves logs of past agent runs so conversations can be `resumed` or analyzed over time.
- `@local-harness/skills`: Manages specialized persona abilities (like code reviews, product management context, database specialization).
- `@local-harness/tool-runtime`: Sandboxed execution engine for safe file reads, path manipulations, shell commands and parsing.
- `@local-harness/trace-bus`: Eventing stream that broadcasts active model states and reasoning traces live to Web/CLI loops (the "Thinking..." visual stream).
- `@local-harness/workspace-policy`: Evaluator that rigorously enforces directory boundaries depending on permission modes (read-only vs workspace-write modes).

### Shared Upstream Depots and Tooling
- `base_repos/` and `third_party/`:
  These directories act as preserved "vendor" clones of reference repositories: `claw-code` (reference for CLI features & slash commands), `agency-agents` (library of specialized prompts), `openclaw`, and `Prompt-Engineering-Guide`.
- `scripts/`: Assorted bash & Node.js CI/local tasks utilized for cross-checking builds, copying vendor configurations, or benchmarking agent responses.
- `tests/`: End-to-End browser checks, CLI binary expectations, Integration workflows, and localized Unit testing paths testing `packages`.
- `docs/`: Technical documents retaining design decisions (Decision Records), architecture diagrams, local UX plans, and capability parity charts.
